					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hornby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1259135); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1259135&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183142" alt="Hornby" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1259135)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hornby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1259135); return false;" >Hornby</a></span> <span class="odate time_1336370706 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 May 2012 06:05</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1440590">
									

<p>An MTF guide might be nice, but I'd caution against it necessarily assuming all MTFs operate like US Marines or SWAT teams. There are plenty of articles where they're treated as men-in-black-suits, rather than commandos.</p>
<p>Also, while civilians may not know by experience what combat is like, it is possible for civilians to understand how military operations work; how military personnel conduct themselves towards their subordinates, equals, and superiors; what tactics are; how logistics are handled; how the psychological factors of combat affect individuals. These are all knowable and learnable without first hand experience (though first hand experience will often teach these lessons faster and more thoroughly).</p>

							</div>

								
					
