														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1441242">
									

<p>He's got just cause, to be honest.</p>
<p>One point I do disagree with, though, is that officers stopped making a career out of getting their men killed after WWI/WWII. There will always be someone that doesn't know what they are doing that will be concerned with their rank/awards/etc. or shouldn't be in command (often at the BEGINNING of conflicts) that don't think of them as men put as pieces on a board. They generally don't last long, just far too long.</p>
<p>The book that Dr Amaeus mentioned looked decent, but the usual &quot;sanitized for public consumption&quot; stuff. I was going to suggest <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Fiction-fact-Dunks-almanac-Old-fashioned/dp/B0006YQYSC">Fiction and Fact from Dunc's Almanac</a>, <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Green-Side-Marine-Corps-Stories/dp/B000NLINY6/ref=sr_1_8?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1336417256&amp;sr=1-8">Green Side Out</a> <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Brown-Side-Out-Marine-Sea-Stories/dp/B000LNT5VQ/ref=sr_1_3?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1336417256&amp;sr=1-3">Brown Side out</a> <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Circles-Marine-Corps-Sea-Stories-Book/dp/0945307039/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1336417256&amp;sr=1-1">Run in circles</a> <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Scream-Shout-Marine-Corps-Sea-Stories/dp/B0006YQYO6/ref=sr_1_14?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1336417343&amp;sr=1-14">Scream and Shout</a> but they're out of print. They give a better understanding of the mentality.</p>

							</div>

								
					
